##How did Shanghai ring the alarm bells in time for the new crown?

Lifeweek

Features an introduction to a magazine and the life he advocates.

In Shanghai, a metropolis of 24 million, the number of confirmed cases per day has been in single digits since Feb. 9. Throughout the outbreak period, there was no major outbreak, no infection by medical staff, and the cure rate for confirmed cases reached 80 per cent.

While the new crown outbreak was a major emergency, the feel of Shanghai was clean and orderly. In a very short period of time, everyone knows where they should stand and what to do. Citizens quickly reached a consensus on "smothering the virus" , community workers pulled nets to screen for high-probability sources of infection and cut off transmission routes, and 110 fever clinics were used as outposts to identify confirmed cases, all confirmed cases were admitted to the Shanghai Clinical Centre for Public Health in Jinshan District. All the departments and offices in Shanghai related to NCP, the best medical resources are concentrated in the public health center to help patients fight with the virus. Every step of its treatment is worth taking as a sample to see how far the epidemic has progressed.

By Yang Lu
Photography | Cheung Lui

By Yang Lu
Photography | Cheung Lui

You don't have to declare an outbreak to take precautions

Lu Hongzhou's Shanghai Public Clinical Center, formerly known as the Shanghai Infectious Disease Hospital, is about 50 kilometers from the city center, and the nearby hospital even passes through farmland. Although it is a third-class hospital, but now tightly guarded, do not accept general patients. According to the city's division of Infectious Diseases, the 110 fever clinics were outposts for new coronaviruses, and all confirmed cases there were sent to the hospital, far from the city. It is the last line of Defense and the main battlefield of the new pneumonia epidemic in Shanghai.

In the wake of SARS, the city of Shanghai built a permanent, Infectious Disease Containment and treatment fortress on Jinshan District's 500 acre compound. Because the positioning in the protection of Shanghai, and even the country's biological safety, although it is a day-to-day triple-a hospital, vigilance has never been relaxed. In the age of globalization, the flight time of a plane can be brought in by passengers without an epidemic far away. Public Health centres routinely collect information on global outbreaks, such as the 2013 H7N9 avian influenza.

On the streets of Shanghai on February 20th, when the outbreak was an emergency, the city's handling of it was orderly

The Shanghai Public Health Center is quick to respond to this new outbreak of pneumonia. On December 31, the Chinese CDC issued an alert to the World Health Organization Organization, the Wuhan CDC issued an alert to the public, and the next day, the Shanghai Public Health Center began to mobilize in accordance with normal procedures. Zhu Tongyu, director of the Shanghai Public Health Center, told our reporter: "during the two-day training, the doctors, nurses, logistics and security personnel of the Public Health Center all participated. Once the patient arrived at the hospital, he was guided to which elevator and which building, what preparations the doctors should make, and what preparations the echelon should make were all rehearsed. On Jan. 6, the Public Health Center set up a special emergency office to deal with unexplained pneumonia in Wuhan. These preparations began to play a role in the treatment of the first subsequent confirmed case of new crown pneumonia, until now."

A medical worker sprays disinfectant outside the Shanghai Stock Exchange building on Feb. 3

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At the time, it was not clear what was known about the unexplained pneumonia in Wuhan. Lu Hongzhou, the party secretary of the Shanghai Public Health Center, said the hypothetical disease used by all of them in the exercise was Middle East Respiratory Syndrome. Middle East Respiratory Syndrome, an acute form of respiratory tract infection, and SARS were among the two most serious infectious diseases caused by the coronavirus until the new pneumonia was confirmed. Lu Hongzhou is a clinical expert of the avian influenza, which studies the diagnosis, treatment and pathogenesis of Infectious Diseases, and the 2013 H7N9 prevention and control campaign, it is he sounded the alarm: to Receive Hospital Emergency Arrangement of hospital infection prevention and control work, specimens sent to the laboratory to focus on the possibility of new viruses. The prevention and control of that time was praised by the World Health Organization Organization as "fast, efficient and professional. " . The WHO has also established the Emerging Infectious Diseases in Shanghai and appointed Lu Hongzhou as its director.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Lu Hongzhou, secretary of the Party Committee of Shanghai Public Health Center

In addition to the internal previews of the epidemic, the Public Health Center also conducted a popular science to Shanghai residents. "So far 27 cases have been found, of which 7 cases are in serious condition. No obvious human-to-human transmission has been found and no infection among medical staff was found, " the Wuhan Health and Health Commission said in its announcement of the pneumonia outbreak in official website at 13:38 p.m. on Dec. 31, shanghai Public Health Center in Shanghai local "Shangguan News" on the "Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission to notify the epidemic of pneumonia, winter and spring "viral pneumonia" how to prevent, experts teach you to remember the three tactics" for the topic of pneumonia prevention popular science. On January 9, Lu Hongzhou reminded the public again in the local media that even if the weather is cold, they should pay attention to the ventilation in their homes and offices, which can reduce the amount of virus in the air and thus reduce the number of infections. If a family member or office colleague becomes ill during the epidemic season, others should be quarantined to reduce the chance of transmission. Avoid crowded places during viral pneumonia and flu season. Go out to take the subway, public transportation and so on after going home, must change the coat promptly, washes the hand, washes the nose.

After the new crown pneumonia outbreak, who has the power to announce the outbreak, and the timing of the announcement has become the focus of accountability. In the view of experienced epidemiologist, legal disclosure is not inconsistent with taking measures to control the epidemic. "No one will stop the local community from taking preventive control measures, " said Zhang Zuofeng, associate dean of the Public Health at Ucla and a senior tenured professor of epidemiology. This year is already a high incidence of pneumonia, preventive measures can not only control the possible outbreak of new pneumonia, but also reduce other types of pneumonia. Because they're both pneumonia and they take similar precautions. Wouldn't that be nice?"

The Shanghai Public Health Center's practice of maintaining vigilance and taking measures in advance within its area of responsibility when the epidemic of NCP has not been declared as "human-to-human transmission" and the new virus has not been fully studied, is the field of infectious disease prevention and control of professional quality. "Although the cause of the disease is not clear and the severity of the disease is not clear, it does not affect immediate protective measures, " Zhang said. If we know the source of infection and the route of transmission, we cut off the source of infection and the route of transmission. If it's respiratory, we wear masks, if it's close contact, we wash our hands, if there's an intermediate host, we kill the intermediate host. Prevention and control measures should be taken before we understand the causes and complex mechanisms of the disease."

On the streets of Shanghai on February 17th, prevention and control requires the mobilization of the whole society

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
89.11% homology to SARS

In fact, epidemiologist can smell an infection from early cases. "The case on December 1 has no history of exposure to the south China seafood market, suggesting that human-to-human transmission may have occurred at the outset, as well as the possibility of small-scale community infections, " Zhang said. The case on December 26 was a family cluster of three with a high risk of human-to-human transmission. There is not too much fog in the air that prevents us from taking precautions."

Zhang, who is overseas, has long been concerned about the development of new coronary pneumonia. "To be honest, it's not human-to-human, " he says. "It's probably still very Emerging Infectious Diseases. In early January of this year, I had a discussion with one of the country's most influential experts on the SARS epidemic. We were both wondering why the initial verdict on the respiratory infection was 'no evidence of human to human transmission' and 'preventable and controllable' ? Presumably to prevent mass panic and maintain social stability. But such thinking, applied in the early stages of the Emerging Infectious Diseases outbreak, objectively delayed the opportunity to take timely and effective preventive measures to control the outbreak, thus contributing to a national pandemic of new coronavirus pneumonia."

On February 17, a district in Shanghai was closed not only for surveillance, but also for undercover checks by district leaders

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
It didn't take long for Shanghai's epidemiologist to deduce the cause of the unexplained pneumonia, because they soon got the results of their scientific study of the virus. Unlike the third-class hospitals, the Shanghai Public Health Center has strong scientific research capabilities, it has Shanghai's first P3 laboratory. In the past five years, Zhang Yongzhen and his team have discovered more than 2,000 new viruses from China. There are about 4,000 to 5,000 named viruses in the world, that means Zhang and his team have found the equivalent of more than a third of the world's named viruses. In addition to the research results, the research led Zhang and his team to build a world-leading, high-throughput sequencing system for the discovery of new viruses, capable of sequencing unknown viruses in the fastest possible time.

Zhang's team has collaborated with the Wuhan Central Hospital and the Wuhan Center for Disease Control and Prevention because they have been working on the new virus. On Jan. 3, Zhang Yongzhen's team took less than 40 hours to get samples of the unknown pneumonia virus from Wuhan. On Jan. 5, they obtained the full genome sequence of the virus and drew an evolutionary tree based on the test data, the COVID-19 proved to be unprecedented in history. Disturbingly, this virus is 89.11% homology to the SARS-causing coronavirus. Lu Hongzhou told the Financial Times that on January 5, they presented this discovery, and their interpretation of this finding "given that the virus is homologous to the SARS coronavirus, should be transmitted via respiratory tract, recommended appropriate prevention and control measures in public places as well as antiviral treatment in clinical treatment" , to the National Board of Health.

What does 89.11% homology mean? Professor Qiu Hong Wang of Ohio State University is a virologist. His laboratory focuses on enteric calicivirus and coronavirus. She explained to our reporter: "after sequencing, know it is with SARS coronavirus homology has 80% , can not be said to be human-to-human transmission, but also to combine epidemiological information. ". Of the six coronaviruses discovered so far, four that are less pathogenic are quite different from SARS, but the gene sequence of the coronaviruses of the new pneumonia is closer to SARS, so we should be alert."Theoretically speaking, the virus sequencing only knows its type, and its severity can only be judged by its infectivity, virulence, and lethality, but if it does, it will require more clinical samples, it also means the outbreak is spreading.

The newly discovered coronavirus has not found the obvious person-to-person transmission, also must treat it as the person-to-person transmission. "Many viruses have just passed from animal to human, and there is no obvious human-to-human transmission, either because it has just found a new host with little infectivity or because the sample size is not large enough, " Wang said. This is the RNA virus of NCP, which mutates very quickly, and it can change every time it infects a person and excretes from that person. As more people become infected, they may become more comfortable with their new host, becoming human-to-human. So, ideally, by cutting off its transmission early on, the virus would not find a next host, reducing the path of evolution in the human population, and it would be eliminated."

It was no secret that the results of the whole genome sequence were soon published on a global scale. On Jan. 9, Xu Jianguo, an academician at the Chinese Academy of Engineering, announced that an expert panel had determined that the pathogen in the case of viral pneumonia of unknown origin was COVID-19. "The COVID-19 of this epidemic is different from the human coronavirus that has been found, " Xu Jianguo told Xinhua. "further scientific research is needed to better understand the virus. "

Wang Qiuhong's lab focuses on coronaviruses, but she doesn't think it's a cold professional judgment to draw conclusions about the need to be wary of the new coronavirus. "The combination of clinical experts in China, epidemiologists who have experienced SARS, and virologists who do research on coronaviruses should be able to come to the same conclusion as me, " Wang said. Zhang's style also played a role in this epidemic, the timing of human-to-human transmission was questioned: "after the gene sequencing, it was found to be a coronavirus, with many similarities to SARS, and even more to human-to-human transmission, coupled with the first case in December of three-person transmission with no history of exposure to the seafood market, why insist that it was not human-to-human transmission, or so-called no evidence of human-to-human transmission? "? I don't know what the reason is. It doesn't make sense."

CITIZEN: The alarm bell sounded very quickly

Shanghai, a megacity with a population of more than 24 million, has not breathed a sigh of relief at the single-digit daily number of confirmed cases since Feb. 9, even as the resumption of work approaches. When the community was just closed, only in the door to check the pass, we interview this week, also want to check out. The Guard told us that residents who were worried about going out of the neighborhood during the quarantine period had to wait until the period of quarantine had expired before they could get a pass.

On Feb. 21, the Shanghai Hongqiao Railway Station was a checkpoint to enter Shanghai, where they had to take temperature readings and register their movements

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Even with freedom of movement, citizens spend most of their time at home. The Shanghainese who can see clearly have reached a high degree of unity in the matter of "smothering the virus" . The difficulty of Shanghai's epidemic prevention and control is not that residents do not attach importance to it. On the contrary, the workload comes from residents'hope that every drop of water will be covered. "We often get calls from residents who say they hear the door of their neighbors' houses, which have been vacant for a long time, ringing. They are afraid to go outside and ask the residents' committee to knock on the door. They must meet each other and ask where people are coming from, " Tang said. If the street to key areas back to Shanghai isolated residents installed alarm magnetic strip, as long as the door, the General Control Center and the Neighborhood Secretary's mobile phone will pop up messages. In addition to making sure you don't go out, you're proving to your neighbors that the neighborhood is safe. Before the magnetic strips were installed, neighbors became nervous when they heard about a medical quarantine in the building, called the 12345, worried about people not staying at home, and even asked the community to post people at People's doors 24 hours a day.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 22, people in Shanghai reached a high degree of consensus on the issue of "smothering the virus" , relying heavily on online shopping for daily needs

After Hepatitis A in 1988 and SARS in 2003, many Shanghainese were quick to sound the alarm about infectious diseases. Citizen Yu Teacher (not her real name) said that in early January, someone in her mother's group sent a message about unexplained pneumonia in Wuhan. "The emergency response of my brain immediately reminded me of SARS. I was still in school, and my temperature was taken first thing in the morning, signed by my parents. Once a student gets hot, the entire class is quarantined. Think of SARS, probably is Shanghai people prepare for a rainy day character, I told the family old man to prepare masks, he also ordered the N95."Fish teacher said. On January 20, as soon as the news of the new human-to-human transmission of pneumonia was announced, the masks on the market in Shanghai were sold out. "among my friends, women are particularly aware. Men and elders may not feel serious at first, washing their hands and wearing masks are reluctant, but as the report goes on, they have also changed from passive cooperation to active initiative,"Yu said.

This precaution is also reflected in the strategic reserve of the Shanghai Public Health Center. "when the hospital was designed in 2004, we made a prediction that 327 beds would be able to cope with the epidemic, based on the likely operational situation of the Emerging Infectious Diseases and the need for isolation treatment, so we built four negative pressure wards, " Lu said. In the event of an outbreak that 327 beds could not cope with, the hospital was built with 600 beds set aside, and another 600 beds could be built in two weeks. The plan was that once half of the 327 beds were used, work on the reserved beds would begin, rather than waiting until they were full. This time around, as a precaution, we've activated 200 of the reserved beds. I guess this time it's just a reserve. There's still one building left out of the 327 beds in the first phase."

Bed Space is very important in the fight against NCP. Lu Hongzhou said: "Most of this disease is mild, a few are severe, not terrible, or there are ways. ". The key is to let the bed and other people, all the infected all admitted to treatment, the source of infection will be controlled. The increase in confirmed and suspected cases went down. Shanghai is positive for all, there is no home isolation. Even with four rooms and a living room, there are still a lot of problems at home. If the beds are tight, we can add beds, because if it's a mild case, it's the same virus and living together won't have much effect on each other."

In addition to the negative pressure beds, equipment for fighting infectious diseases is also a daily reserve at the Shanghai Public Health Center. "after the new crown outbreak, we don't need to buy temporary equipment, " Lu said. The Public Health Center, these medical devices, routinely prepare for five days of consumption, depending on how many patients there were. There is a reserve of protective clothing, masks and positive pressure inhalers, especially positive pressure inhalers, we are negative pressure wards, and then use positive pressure inhalers is a double insurance, medical staff will not be infected. We have done a lot to protect the medical team,"he said

Patients at the fever clinic of Oriental Hospital are given throat swabs on Feb. 18

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
During our interview, we met a lot of suitcases in the lobby of the administration building, which is the luggage of the medical staff of the hospital in Shanghai. In addition to centralizing the confirmed cases in public health centers, Shanghai has also adopted the method of Centralizing Superior Medical Resources this time. Experts and medical forces from departments related to the new pneumonia in the city will be mobilized to work in public health centers at any time, about 170 foreign aid doctors come to the public health center to stay or attend consultations. Zhang Wenhong, director of infection department of Mount Hua Hospital, Mao Enqiang, director of Emergency Department of Ruijin Hospital, Zhu Lei, professor of Smoking Department of Zhongshan Hospital and Hu Bijie, director of infection department, formed the medical treatment expert group. Each day, they discuss their patients'treatment plans remotely with doctors stationed in the negative-pressure Ward. The Public Health Center has a P3 laboratory that collects and tests specimens from confirmed patients on a daily basis, which is then used as a reference for clinical practice. The expert group, the doctors use their own clinical experience, these fine data, for each inpatient to develop their own treatment plan, "one by one, " "one person, one policy.

The Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center did what it was supposed to do, setting up checkpoints from the prevention and control of the epidemic to meticulous treatment. As of this publication, 335 confirmed cases had been found in the city of 24 million people, and 249 had been cured and discharged from hospital, the cured discharge rate was 74.3% .
